            <section class="prose">
              <h2>What is the present value of an annuity?</h2>
              <p>
                The <strong>present value of an annuity</strong> is the lump sum
                today that is financially equivalent to a series of equal
                payments in the future, discounted at a given interest (or
                discount) rate. It answers questions like:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  How much is a pension that pays $2,000 per month for 20 years
                  worth today?
                </li>
                <li>
                  What lump sum today is equivalent to receiving $10,000 per
                  year for the next 15 years?
                </li>
                <li>
                  How much should I pay for an annuity contract or structured
                  settlement?
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Present value of ordinary annuity vs annuity due</h2>
              <p>There are two common types of annuities:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Ordinary annuity</strong> – payments occur at the
                  <em>end</em> of each period (most loans, bonds, and many
                  pensions).
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Annuity due</strong> – payments occur at the
                  <em>beginning</em> of each period (rent, many leases, some
                  insurance products).
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Because annuity-due payments arrive one period earlier, they are
                discounted for fewer periods and are therefore worth
                <strong>more</strong> today than an equivalent ordinary annuity.
              </p>

              <h2>Formulas for the present value of an annuity</h2>

              <h3>1. Ordinary level annuity (no growth)</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Formula</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ PV_{\text{ordinary}} = Pmt \times \frac{1 - (1 +
                  r)^{-n}}{r} \]
                </p>
                <p><strong>Where:</strong></p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\(PV\) = present value of the annuity</li>
                  <li>\(Pmt\) = payment per period</li>
                  <li>\(r\) = interest (discount) rate per period</li>
                  <li>\(n\) = total number of periods</li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <h3>2. Annuity due (payments at beginning of period)</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Formula</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ PV_{\text{due}} = PV_{\text{ordinary}} \times (1 + r) \] or
                  directly: \[ PV_{\text{due}} = Pmt \times \frac{1 - (1 +
                  r)^{-n}}{r} \times (1 + r) \]
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>3. Growing annuity (payments grow at rate g)</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Formula (ordinary growing annuity)</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ PV_{\text{growing}} = Pmt_1 \times \frac{1 - \left(\frac{1
                  + g}{1 + r}\right)^n}{r - g} \]
                </p>
                <p><strong>Where:</strong></p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\(Pmt_1\) = first payment amount</li>
                  <li>\(g\) = growth rate per period of the payments</li>
                  <li>
                    \(r\) = discount rate per period (must satisfy \(r \neq g\))
                  </li>
                </ul>
                <p>
                  For a <strong>growing annuity due</strong>, multiply the
                  result by \((1 + r)\).
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>Worked example: PV of a level ordinary annuity</h2>
              <p>
                Suppose you will receive <strong>$1,000 per month</strong> for
                <strong>10 years</strong>, and the appropriate discount rate is
                <strong>6% per year</strong>, compounded monthly.
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>Payment per period: \(Pmt = 1{,}000\).</li>
                <li>Monthly rate: \(r = 0.06 / 12 = 0.005\).</li>
                <li>Total periods: \(n = 10 \times 12 = 120\).</li>
                <li>
                  Apply the ordinary annuity formula: \[ PV = 1{,}000 \times
                  \frac{1 - (1 + 0.005)^{-120}}{0.005} \]
                </li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                Evaluating the factor \(\dfrac{1 - (1 + 0.005)^{-120}}{0.005}
                \approx 90.97\), so: \[ PV \approx 1{,}000 \times 90.97 =
                \$90{,}970 \]
              </p>
              <p>
                This means receiving $1,000 per month for 10 years is roughly
                equivalent to receiving about <strong>$90,970 today</strong> at
                a 6% annual discount rate.
              </p>

              <h2>Common use cases</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Retirement planning:</strong> valuing pension or
                  annuity income streams.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Loan analysis:</strong> understanding how much a
                  payment schedule is worth today.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Structured settlements:</strong> pricing legal
                  settlements or lottery payouts.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Investment comparison:</strong> comparing a lump-sum
                  offer to a series of future payments.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Limitations and assumptions</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  The discount rate and growth rate are assumed to be constant
                  over the entire term.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Payments are assumed to be exactly equal and occur at regular
                  intervals.
                </li>
                <li>
                  The calculator does not model taxes, fees, inflation, or
                  default risk explicitly.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>

              <h3>
                Is a higher discount rate better or worse for present value?
              </h3>
              <p>
                A higher discount rate <strong>reduces</strong> the present
                value of an annuity. That is because future cash flows are
                discounted more heavily, making them worth less today.
              </p>

              <h3>What discount rate should I use?</h3>
              <p>It depends on context. Common choices include:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Your expected investment return (opportunity cost of capital).
                </li>
                <li>
                  A risk-free rate plus a risk premium for uncertain cash flows.
                </li>
                <li>The interest rate on comparable loans or bonds.</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Can the present value of an annuity be negative?</h3>
              <p>
                Mathematically, yes, if you treat payments you make as negative
                cash flows. In practice, we usually quote the absolute value and
                interpret the sign based on whether you are paying or receiving
                the annuity.
              </p>
